    <h1>School Project: Functional Hardware for PCs</h1>

    <h2>Objective</h2>
    <p>To educate and create awareness about the key functional hardware components of a personal computer (PC), their roles, and how they work together to create a fully functional system.</p>

    <h2>Key Functional Hardware Components</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>CPU (Central Processing Unit)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Description:</strong> Known as the brain of the PC, the CPU executes instructions and performs calculations.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Processes data and controls the flow of information within the computer.</li>
                <li><strong>Examples:</strong> Intel Core i9, AMD Ryzen 9</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Motherboard</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Description:</strong> The main circuit board that connects all hardware components.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Provides pathways for data and power to travel between components.</li>
                <li><strong>Key Parts:</strong> Chipset, RAM slots, CPU socket, Peripheral connectors</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>RAM (Random Access Memory)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Description:</strong> Temporary storage used to hold data that the CPU accesses quickly.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Improves multitasking and processing speed.</li>
                <li><strong>Examples:</strong> DDR4, DDR5</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Storage Devices</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>HDD:</strong> Traditional storage using magnetic disks.</li>
                <li><strong>SSD:</strong> Faster, modern storage with no moving parts.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Stores the operating system, software, and files.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>PSU (Power Supply Unit)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Description:</strong> Converts electricity from an outlet into usable power for the PC.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Supplies stable power to all hardware components.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>GPU (Graphics Processing Unit)</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Description:</strong> Specialized hardware for rendering images, videos, and animations.</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Crucial for gaming, video editing, and 3D rendering.</li>
                <li><strong>Examples:</strong> NVIDIA RTX 4090, AMD Radeon RX 7900 XTX</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Cooling Systems</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Types:</strong> Air cooling, Liquid cooling systems</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Keeps hardware components at an optimal temperature to prevent overheating.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Input/Output Devices</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Input:</strong> Keyboard, Mouse, Webcam</li>
                <li><strong>Output:</strong> Monitor, Speakers, Printer</li>
                <li><strong>Function:</strong> Facilitates user interaction with the PC.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How These Components Work Together</h2>
    <p>
        1. The CPU retrieves data from storage and processes it with the help of RAM.<br>
        2. The motherboard facilitates communication between the CPU, GPU, and other peripherals.<br>
        3. The GPU handles graphic-intensive tasks and outputs visuals to the monitor.<br>
        4. The PSU ensures every component receives the power it needs.
    </p>

    <h2>Hands-On Activity Suggestion</h2>
    <p>
        Task: Build a PC using basic hardware components.<br>
        Presentation: Label each component and explain its role during a class presentation.
    </p>

    <h2>Fun Facts</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>The first commercial CPU, the Intel 4004, was released in 1971 and had only 2,300 transistors.</li>
        <li>Modern GPUs can perform over 10 trillion operations per second.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Potential Issues and Troubleshooting</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Common Hardware Failures:</strong> Overheating, Power supply issues, Faulty RAM</li>
        <li><strong>Basic Troubleshooting Tips:</strong> Clean components, Check connections, Replace defective parts</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
        Understanding functional hardware is crucial for anyone interested in technology. By learning about these components, students can better appreciate how PCs work and troubleshoot basic hardware issues. This knowledge is essential in a world increasingly reliant on technology.
    </p>

    <h2>References</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>PC hardware manuals</li>
        <li>Reputable tech websites</li>
        <li>Textbooks</li>
    </ul>
